Anti-CAA protests in Mumbai: The Aurangabad Bench said those protesting against the Citizenship (Amendment) Act â€œcannot be called traitorsâ€. Anti-CAA protests in Mumbai: The Aurangabad Bench said those protesting against the Citizenship (Amendment) Act â€œcannot be called traitorsâ€.

Setting aside an order by the Additional District Magistrate against allowing protests in Maharashtraâ€™s Beed, the Aurangabad Bench of the Bombay High Court said that those protesting against the Citizenship (Amendment) Act â€œcannot be called traitors, anti-nationals only because they want to oppose one lawâ€.

The Court said that an agitation cannot be suppressed only on the ground that people are agitating against the government. It also asked the bureaucracy to â€œkeep in mindâ€ that when people believe that a â€œparticular Act is an attack on their rightsâ€¦ they are bound to defend that rightâ€. And underlined that it is not for the Court â€œto ascertain whether the exercise of such right will create a law and order problemâ€.

Granting relief to petitioners who were seeking permission to sit at a location for an indefinite agitation, the Court noted they had given an undertaking that no slogans would be raised against the country, any religion, or unity and integrity of the nation.

